The ability to restore Confluence from an XML backup is great if your datasource has somehow been corrupted; however, if your datasource is okay and it is Confluence that has become corrupted it would seem to be more reasonable to restore the site from the database directly.  Would it be possible to create a restore procedure in the datasource to restore a site?  It seems if the site can be XML encoded, then it could be encoded in the datasource and updated during reindexing.  This way, in the event that Confluence is corrupted, the site could be restored from the datasource and contain the most recent data, rather than data from a backup ran several hours (or even days) earlier.  I think it would be an incredibly useful feature, especially when you consider the potential for environment replication.

